Title: Sink Is Busted
Comment: What people call post rock today has way more in common with shoegaze then the original post rock bands, to the point where the waves of this genre should be given completely different names instead of trying to link them historically somehow. How the scene that gave us bands as diverse as June of 44 and US maple turned into a bunch of Godspeed clones of varying quality, all just playing pretty guitar lines that crescendo over and over, is beyond me.

Title: Musical Preference

Comment: I really fucking hate sublime

Title: Soul Kitchen - 2017 Remaster
Comment: OPINION: So many people these days are always saying they don’t like The Doors and they “just don’t understand how they could be so popular” (tedious!) that we’ve officially come full circle to the point that now it’s cool and non-mainstream and contrarian to come out and say actually the band does NOT suck. Secondary opinion: Any band that heavily features the organ is elite. I would have submitted “Light My Fire” but the Doors-haters wouldn’t be able to get through the 8 minutes.

Title: Von

More bands should be honest with themselves and treat the voice as an instrument. The idea of "Hopelandic" is a pretty honest acknowledgment of what I want out of vocals in music. There are 1% of lyrics that I care about. Most suck/are boring. Also, I heard an interview with Jónsi where he said he mostly only listens to bird noises, which is exactly what I wanted from him.

Title: Human
Comment: “Are we human, or are we dancer”, words that will live in infamy. Yes, I know it’s a Hunter S. Thompson reference. No, that doesn’t make it any less clunky. He could’ve done us a solid and made dancer plural so at least it wouldn’t be structural nails on a chalkboard.

Title: Again I Go Unnoticed
Album: The Places You Have Come to Fear the Most
Comment:
"Please send me anything but signals that are mixed."

Can't he just find a way to say "mixed signals?"
Do we really need the Yoda phrasing to make this work?

P.S. I did google this, and its called Anastrophe: a figure of speech in which the normal word order of the subject, the verb, and the object is changed. For example, subject–verb–object ("I like potatoes") might be changed to object–subject–verb ("potatoes I like"). And Yoda is mentioned on the wiki page.

Title: Empire State Of Mind
Comment:
"concrete jungle where dreams are made of" ???

this song is way too popular/made by huge artists to have such a weird grammatical thing in the CHORUS. it drives me insane every time i hear it. it also doesn't rhyme with the next line ("there's nothing you can't do") - despite the rest of the chorus having an AA/BB rhyme scheme - so it's not like "of" had to be the last word. i'm getting madder typing this all out

Title: ABCs

Title: Kids
Comment: This is a great song, but that double negative in the chorus always bothers. It's such a kinda generic line - they definitely could have worked up something better.

Title: Anything You Want
Comment: Yeah, you already said you like it rough, and you can say it twice or however many times you want if it sounds good. HOWEVER, drawing attention to it and pointing out that you're saying it twice just makes me think you couldn't think of any better line to go there. There's already a ton of repetition in the song, and you're singling out one line? Either own it or fix it, fuck

Title: For You and I
Comment: Pronouns serving as objects of prepositions take the objective case.  I fully support breaking grammar rules for creativity, dialect, etc., but there is no rhyme-related or artistic reason that she couldn’t use the correct pronoun (“me”) instead. In the first chorus, it would even rhyme better with “dream.” The “you and I” repeats constantly in this song just to taunt me and it’s also IN THE ACTUAL TITLE. Side note: It’s musically the weakest track on a beautiful album.

Comment: I'm calling this song title pretentious because it's artificially complex. It is a deliberate effort to make this song seem more intricate than it actually is. Title: When Did My Hair Get So Long
Comment:
"My mother, my sister, I try my best to mend you, but" is what I hear in the beginning, and it setup a theme (in my head) of some familial trauma which would be a jumping off point for the song's theme of impermanence. Instead it's "I'm not that persistent, I try my best and then give up", which isn't any catalytic event and is more of the same stuff already littered throughout the song.

It's still a jam, though.

Title: You Oughta Know
Comment: The common “cross-eyed bear” mishearing in the chorus is for amateurs. Instead: “it’s not fair/to the night air/all across Siber’ that you gave to me.” This is superior to the original.  1. “Air” rhymes with “fair.” “Me” absolutely does not. 2. Siber’, of course, is a nickname for Siberia, which is known to have very cold night air. And day air, probably. 3. “Night air all across Siber’” is brutal and expansive and bleak. Not something very nice to give to someone! I was 11 but it all holds up.

Title: Smoke on the Water
Comment:
For years when we were kids, my dad always used to sing "snow-covered water" when this came on.

At some point when I was a teenager, my mom finally had to pull me aside and tell me, "it's actually 'smoke on the water,' but your father just likes his version better."

To this day, I still have to check myself. It's hard to remember which is right, but "snow-covered water" feels right.
